{"slug":"brokers","graph":"companies","title":"The brokers","sub":"who can broker introductions across the market's gaps","headline":"The labs aside, the market's best-placed broker is <strong>LangChain (LangGraph / LangSmith) (constraint 0.09, 15 ties across 5 verticals)</strong> — and counting only real business ties, the seat passes to Microsoft (0.11).","prose":{"intro":"<p>Who in this market can actually broker an introduction? Not the best-connected company — the one whose contacts don't already know each other. That company sits across the open gaps between clusters, and those gaps are where deal flow, hiring, and early market intelligence move first.</p>","how":"<p>The score, called constraint, measures how much a company's contacts overlap: high when all its ties fold back into one tight clique, low when its contacts are strangers to each other and it alone connects them. Low constraint is what makes a broker. Effective size is the companion number — a tie count discounted for redundancy, so 12 contacts who all know each other count as far fewer than 12 independent ones. We rank the 171 companies in the map's main connected cluster from least constrained to most, keeping the 132 with at least 3 ties (39 smaller nodes are excluded — with one or two ties, the score says nothing). Then we re-run on business edges only — customer, partner, and platform relationships — because a bridge made of shared-investor edges may never convert to a warm intro. The second table is the honest broker list.</p>","method":"<p>Burt (1992), <em>Structural Holes</em>: constraint c<sub>i</sub> = Σ<sub>j</sub>(p<sub>ij</sub> + Σ<sub>q</sub> p<sub>iq</sub>p<sub>qj</sub>)²; effective size via the Borgatti (1997) simplification for binary graphs; networkx implementations of both. Full mixed run: giant component of the company graph (171 nodes, 474 edges; smaller components excluded — constraint is a local statistic, so this only drops their few eligible members). Business-only run: giant component of the business-edge subgraph (75 nodes, 112 edges, 26 nodes over the degree floor). The funding graph was checked and not shipped: it has zero triangles (a forest), so constraint reduces to exactly 1/degree for all 33 nodes over the floor — the statistic would restate degree and nothing else.</p>"},"caveat":"AoC's own 5 edges are 4 competitor ties plus one unverified business tie (AIUC), so its seat in the full-map table (constraint 0.20, rank 38 of 132) mostly reflects rivalry — and in the business-only map, AoC and AIUC connect only to each other, so AoC is absent from the warm-intro list entirely. Note also that none of the top 25 full-map brokers are VCs: the mapped VCs sit at the market's edge, not in its gaps.","inputs":{"companies":{"nodes":188,"edges":492}},"data":{"brokers":[{"id":"anthropic","label":"Anthropic","vertical":"frontier lab","degree":45,"constraint":0.047,"effSize":42.2,"spans":6,"flag":null},{"id":"openai","label":"OpenAI","vertical":"frontier lab","degree":30,"constraint":0.066,"effSize":27.3,"spans":6,"flag":null},{"id":"langchain-langgraph-langsmith","label":"LangChain (LangGraph / LangSmith)","vertical":"infra platform","degree":15,"constraint":0.09,"effSize":13.9,"spans":5,"flag":"broker by trade"},{"id":"cognition-devin","label":"Cognition (Devin)","vertical":"agent native startup","degree":16,"constraint":0.102,"effSize":14.1,"spans":7,"flag":null},{"id":"microsoft","label":"Microsoft","vertical":"enterprise other","degree":18,"constraint":0.107,"effSize":15.2,"spans":4,"flag":"broker by trade"},{"id":"glean","label":"Glean","vertical":"agent native startup","degree":12,"constraint":0.111,"effSize":10.5,"spans":6,"flag":null},{"id":"protect-ai-palo-alto-networks","label":"Protect AI (Palo Alto Networks)","vertical":"security eval vendor","degree":16,"constraint":0.112,"effSize":13.8,"spans":3,"flag":null},{"id":"bolt-stackblitz","label":"Bolt (StackBlitz)","vertical":"agent native startup","degree":12,"constraint":0.123,"e